{{nihongo|'''''Tora-san Meets His Lordship'''''|<U+7537><U+306F><U+3064><U+3089><U+3044><U+3088> <U+5BC5><U+6B21><U+90CE><U+3068><U+6BBF><U+69D8>|Otoko wa Tsurai yo: Torajir<U+014D> to Tonosama}} ''aka'' '''''Tora-san and a Lord'''''<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.citwf.com/film257093.htm|title=OTOKO WA TSURAIYO -TORAJIRO TO TONOSAMA|accessdate=2010-01-18|publisher=[[Complete Index to World Film]]}}</ref> is a [[1977 in film|1977]] [[Japan]]ese comedy film directed by [[Yoji Yamada]]. It stars [[Kiyoshi Atsumi]] as Torajir<U+014D> Kuruma (Tora-san), and Ky<U+014D>ko Maya as his love interest or "Madonna".<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.tora-san.jp/toranomaki/movie19/madonna.html|title=<U+7537><U+306F><U+3064><U+3089><U+3044><U+3088> <U+5BC5><U+6B21><U+90CE><U+3068><U+6BBF><U+69D8> (Madonna)|accessdate=2010-01-18|publisher=[http://www.tora-san.jp/ www.tora-san.jp]|language=Japanese}} (official site)</ref> ''Tora-san Meets His Lordship'' is the nineteenth entry in the popular, long-running ''[[Otoko wa Tsurai yo]]'' series.

==Synopsis==
Tora-san returns to his family home in Shibamata, Tokyo, but soon leaves again due to squabbles involving a dog they have named Tora-san. During his travels in Shikoku, Tora-san makes the acquaintance of a descendant of a local ''[[daimy<U+014D>]]''. The old man asks Tora-san to find his son's widow in Tokyo, whom he had previously alienated.<ref name ="Kinejun">{{cite web |url= http://www.kinejun.jp/cinema/id/18723|title= <U+7537><U+306F><U+3064><U+3089><U+3044><U+3088> <U+5BC5><U+6B21><U+90CE><U+3068><U+6BBF><U+69D8>|accessdate=2010-01-18|language=Japanese|publisher=[[Kinema Junpo]]}}</ref><ref name ="Galbraith">{{cite web |first=Stuart |last=Galbraith IV |authorlink= Stuart Galbraith IV|url=http://www.dvdtalk.com/reviews/20443/tora-san-19-tora-san-meets-his-lordship/|title=Tora-san 19: Tora-san meets His Lordship (Region 3) |date=2006-03-02|accessdate=2010-01-18|publisher=[[DVD Talk]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://ftvdb.bfi.org.uk/sift/title/305842|title=OTOKO WA TSURAI YO TORAJIRO TO TONOSAMA (1977)|accessdate=2010-01-18|publisher=[[British Film Institute]]}}</ref>

